In Europe, inflation has spilled over into food
The accelerated inflation, as measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid increase in food prices.
In November, price increases in the 13 euro area countries were higher than forecast, after an inflation rate of 2.6 per cent in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 per cent was recorded, the European Community Statistics Office in Luxembourg reported.
Official forecasts have only suggested 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the US, UK and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the key interest rate by saying that the fall in interest rates, together with rising commodity prices and falling unemployment, would lead to the creation of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep inflation below but close to two per cent.
According to one analyst, this is Catch 22 for the ECB: "we need to deter" inflation so that we do not have to intervene on this subject later.
In Germany, the inflation rate of 3.3 per cent is a record for the last 12 years, and in Spain it has risen from 3.6 to 4.1.
Inflation in the euro area has soared as a result of the rapid rise in food and energy prices.
The forward market shares of cereals have risen by 88 per cent and the price of soybeans has also reached its highest value since 1973.
The price of food oil and dairy products also increased significantly in 2007.
This year, the world oil price has risen 52 percent, and last month, a barrel of black gold was worth nearly $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will fall from 2.1% in 2008 to 2.5% this year, but will fall to 1.9% in 2009.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate remains around 3 percent, however, the next 3 to 4 months, the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to cut the key rate twice in 2008.
Gallup indicates a government crisis
After a long stagnation, the number of supporters of Fidesz (Alliance of Young Democrats) increased significantly in early December, so that it now has the highest number of supporters since 2002, while Gallup (Polling Institute) has never before seen such low socialist support, namely 13 percent.
For the loyal voters, the difference would represent, due to the greater determination of the opposition voters, a support of more than two thirds (71 per cent) against the support of a fifth (20 per cent) for the MSZP (Hungarian Socialist Party).
According to the poll, the MDF (Forum of Hungarian Democrats) and the SZDSZ (Alliance of Free Democrats) are below the threshold of parliamentarians: their support is two percent in the entire population.
Of the loyal voters who were certain to go to the polls, the number of supporters of both parties increased by 1 percent.
The economic climate has continued to deteriorate from the previous low point, the proportion of those who considered the economic situation of the country to be particularly serious has never been higher, it stands at 41 per cent and according to 46 per cent of the supplementary figures the situation is quite serious.
After the more optimistic outlook of last spring and summer, families are once again more pessimistic about their financial situation.
For the next year, the majority of the population expects the situation to worsen and only one tenth expects it to improve.
Last December, 71 per cent of those polled, a majority never seen in previous Gallup polls, thought the Prime Minister was doing his job rather poorly than well.
13 percent of the respondents have confidence or a lot of confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány while 38 percent support Viktor Orbán.
54 percent do not trust the Prime Minister at all and 27 percent the president of Fidesz.
One of the indicators of the change in the political situation is the proportion of society that believes that dissatisfaction with the Prime Minister can be dealt with without a change of government.
While after the October riots, 35 percent of those polled wanted the government and the prime minister to remain in office, the current figure is only 20 percent, with the relative majority (33 percent) believing that holding new elections would be the solution to this situation.
When asked about their intention to vote, 60 per cent of those surveyed said they would certainly vote and an additional 20 per cent said they would probably vote.
To make a comparison, for a "legislative election next Sunday", only 55 percent of those polled would certainly participate and an additional 15 percent would probably participate.
74 percent of people would say no to tuition fees for higher education, 79 percent would say no to consultation fees and 84 percent would say no to hospital stays.
When we look only at the same proportions among the people who expressed their intention to vote in the referendum, respectively 81, 84 and 89 percent of voters would reject the introduction of registration fees, consultation fees and hospital stays.
Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has raised its prices by almost twenty percent
The hypermarkets in the Budaörs shopping triangle maintained the average price increase of 16 per cent from last year, with the difference that this year the VAT rate did not increase.
Article from Napi Gazdaság (Economy of the day)
This year, in the Budaörs shopping triangle, the usual daily Christmas basket also increased by an average of 16 percent, with a value increase of well over one thousand forints in all hypermarkets.
Prices, which had already soared in large food stores in December, have not risen sharply from the previous high base.
Nevertheless, consumers are obviously shocked to see that items purchased for well under 9 000 forints last year now cost more than 10 000 forints.
The daily basket in the hypermarkets surveyed exceeded by 91 forints, at least, the psychological threshold of ten thousand forints.
And the highest value of the basket was 10,573 forints.
(In 2003 this figure was 6,800 forints.)
Prices of Unicum and live fish remained almost at last year's level, but prices of turkey net, nut and poppy have risen sharply.
In the shops, the price of flour and bread followed the data of the KSH (Central Statistics Institute), but in Auchan, one kilo of bread was found at only 139 forints.
Competition has not lowered the price of the product below 200 forints.
It was surprising to see, also in this supermarket, that the price of the registered two-litre bottle of Coca-Cola was less than 200 forints, so it cost only 257 forints the registered bottle included.
However, this year, in terms of daily basket, Auchan was the most expensive and Cora the cheapest.
According to our calculations, Cora raised the price of her daily basket by 15 percent while Tesco and Auchan raised them by about 18 and 18 percent respectively.
Comparing last year's most expensive basket and this year's cheapest basket, we see a 12 percent gap whereas the difference between last year's cheapest and this year's most expensive is 21 percent.
Prices have increased by an average of 1 480 forints.
Last year prices increased by an average of 1 206 forints, although the impact of the VAT rate increase was already noticeable in last year's Christmas prices.
This process has confused the trade, hypermarkets could not clearly determine what margin to apply to products because they were unable to predict the impact of price changes on consumption.
(If a trader miscalculates the turnover of a product, he may lose a large profit on the margin adjusted for the intensity of the trade.)
Due to the change in the VAT rate, the increase in the prices of the Daily Basket has been so excessive that the most expensive basket was 1 720 forints higher than the value of 2006, while the difference between the cheapest baskets was only 844 forints.
This year the difference was not so great, since the most expensive basket was worth 1 630 forints more than last year and the prices of the cheapest also increased by 1 284 forints.
As we approached the two Christmas seasons, we saw a catastrophic price increase, in less than 20 months the prices of everyday consumer goods in supermarkets increased by more than 30 per cent.
(This does not necessarily confirm the KSH data: for some basic foodstuffs, the statistical institute has recorded a price increase of more than 30 per cent in 12 months.
This is the case, for example, with flour and eggs.)
According to the daily newspaper, this seems almost absurd since the price level of this product, which was already very expensive last year, has risen by barely more than 10 per cent compared to the base.
According to the indices, flour suppliers are in a stronger position than egg suppliers because they have succeeded in getting the sharp price increases accepted by multinationals as well.
In the golden triangle of commerce, hypermarkets do not complain, they record consistently good years.
In our experience, most customers no longer look at the prices in the three hypermarkets they visit.
They buy everything in plenty, they take the food that's been stored for a long time in pallets.
On Wednesday morning, large queues formed at the checkout booths of the three hypermarkets as the number of customers increased sharply.
However, according to our information, turnover is less important in the province, many multinationals complain to the survey companies that they do not even reach the expected turnover, not only for food but also for durable consumer goods.
Many hospitals are saving on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, mainly caused by the improper use of antibiotics, were recorded in hospitals.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, the insufficient number of beds, and the overworking of medical staff do not help to stop infections, says the chief medical officer of the National Centre for Epidemiology.
Many hospitals are also saving on disinfectants
Recently, a MRSA infection was diagnosed in the trauma department of the János Hospital.
The antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected in a man hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
Earlier this year, a similar infection occurred in the same area.
The victim of a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital but soon afterwards had to return due to an MRSA infection and since then doctors have been unable to perform a major operation on him because of the bacteria in his body.
As of 10 December this year, 1,094 hospital infections caused by a multi-drug resistant pathogen have been reported to the National Hospital Monitoring System, said Karolina Böröcz, chief medical officer at the National Centre for Epidemiology.
That is, the number of infections caused by a multi-drug resistant pathogen that has actually been recorded in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
Approximately two thirds of the infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, i.e. methicillin-oxacillin-resistant staphylococcus aureus.
One third of people carry the Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their nose without developing disease.
Infections caused by AS (such as angina, tonsillitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) respond well to antibiotics and are easily curable.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacteria that respond well to antibiotics will develop a resistant bacteria that will proliferate rapidly in poor hospital conditions.
If the immune system is temporarily or prolongedly dysfunctional, this bacterium can cause serious hospital infections, such as traumatic infection or sepsis, in elderly, low-weight or weakened patients.
According to the head doctor of the János Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infections, these infections are part of the daily life of hospitals.
Infection should not be confused with epidemic, MRSA is not found only there or not looked for, said Tibor Nyulasi.
The A.S. is resistant to antibiotics.
"These patients are isolated, the healthcare staff puts on rubber gloves and protective masks and we have suitable antibiotics to treat them", said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients in hospitals are usually tested for MRSA, but infection cannot always be prevented.
Sampling is not in vogue
The vast majority of MRSA infections could be prevented but the current conditions and circumstances in Hungarian hospitals are not favourable to prevent the development and proliferation of multi-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection is most prevalent in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should monitor inpatients and isolate MRSA patients immediately.
However, microbiological sampling is not in vogue in Hungarian hospitals.
It should be noted that the National Social Security Fund does not finance these exams.
Most cases only occur if MRSA infection is detectable in the patient, said the head physician of the epidemiological center.
The European Union has strict recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are Hungarian guidelines also for the treatment of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts must be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, i.e. microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent drug resistance but hospitals do not always take this into account.
Microbiological sampling is even rarer in outpatient and primary care, said Karolina Böröcz.
Many hospitals are saving on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA spreads from one patient to another, most often through medical personnel.
It is therefore essential to wash hands, wear gloves and face masks, but there are significant gaps in hospitals in this area as well.
MRSAs are spread by infection transmitted by inhalation of droplets and by contact, however, because of the conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient cannot always be isolated.
In addition, the rooms are often full, the beds are often too close together, whereas in epidemic terms, patients should be kept at least 1.5 metres apart.
Unfortunately, we also see that hospitals in financial difficulty are saving on disinfectants, they lack nurses, there are many patients, so the risk of contamination is even greater, said Karolina Böröcz.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals where preventive measures are followed, the number of infections is demonstrably lower or the spread of the pathogen can be blocked.
Government project against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection is an exorbitant expense for the Social Security funds, which is why we are fighting this infection everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has established a programme to prevent or reduce the incidence of MRSA.
According to published data, this programme is effective and MRSA infections are showing a declining trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) lists as one of its priorities the prevention of the incidence of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
The Commissioner, who caused the fatal accident, was not intoxicated
The official statement of the fatal accident caused by the 22nd Ward Commissioner has been drawn up.
It is possible that the 22nd district commissioner, who has since resigned from his post, who ran over a pedestrian causing his death last Tuesday, would have driven while drunk or dizzy, Attila Morvai, spokesman for the Public Prosecutor's Office of the capital, said on Friday after the relative finding was established.
The findings confirmed the first result of the investigation which had already found that the former Commissioner had not consumed alcohol before he took the wheel
Last Tuesday, the former 22nd Ward police chief ran over a 55-year-old man who was in front of him when he turned his car around on Kossuth Lajos Street in the 22nd Ward, trying to cross the road without going through the pedestrian crossing.
(In fact, the fact that he was crossing the road outside the pedestrian crossing is not a mitigating circumstance, as the Highway Code requires a car starting a turn to let pedestrians through.)
The pedestrian died after being transported to the hospital.
Following the accident, the Commissioner resigned from his post and asked for his retirement because, according to the police report, the accident had upset him deeply.
The investigation of this case is being conducted by the Budapest Prosecutor's Office.
Attila Morvai also mentioned that the former Commissioner cooperated from the beginning with the magistrates in charge of the investigation.
EUR 400 million for infrastructure
Hungary's Finance Minister János Veres and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed three agreements in Budapest on Friday for a credit line worth a total of EUR 400 million to support education, transport and environmental infrastructure and energy.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) adopted a budget of EUR 300 million for the Hungarian budget financing of transport and environmental projects to be carried out from the Cohesion Fund, for which a credit agreement worth EUR 100 million has already been signed by the parties.
The agreement on the EUR 150 million loan also concerns the budgetary financing of projects related to education.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for Hungary, with the remaining EUR 150 million to be used later following the extension of the loan agreement.
The parties have signed a contract for 50 million euros for innovation, the state budget will use this envelope in the first place in the framework of the research and development project to be carried out at the University of Debrecen.
During the negotiations, the project for the metro line 4 was also discussed.
The parties agreed that they would discuss the possible modification of the original contract once Hungary had finalised the details of the financing of the metro with the EU.
According to János Veres, this could be done in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has provided a total of EUR 8.4 billion for the financing of 113 projects in Hungary.
The EIB grants loans at the EURIBOR interest rate, with a grace period of eight years and without a commitment fee.
Bulgaria, a haven for the EU housing market
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is spectacular, and the attention of the whole of Europe is now focused on this little-mentioned Balkan country.
What, or who, bought on this EU market which is still the cheapest but which will soon become expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
Bulgaria is now undoubtedly the most popular destination for real estate in Eastern Europe, with its cheap ski resorts and seaside homes.
In the mountains, the most popular areas are Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa and, by the sea, Albena, the "Golden Sands", the "Sunshine Coast", the former Sozopol and Nessebar but more and more people are looking for a building in the Kavarna and Balcik area as well.
According to Re/Max Bulgaria, sooner or later the central region of the country, namely Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna, will also attract investors and more and more people are also buying in the very cheap corner of Ruse.
The capital Sofia also offers attractive opportunities, with shops and office space offering the highest depreciation rates.
Bulgaria is well on its way to becoming one of the most attractive golfing paradises in Europe and thus a priority destination, after the summer and winter seasons, also in the other two seasons of the year.
The more vigilant investors are already buying in large numbers, for example in the Bansko area.
According to analysts, people who buy a building in Bulgaria are also looking to change their life - their way of life.
Most of the buyers are British but others come from France, Belgium, Spain and increasingly from Romania.
The Maltese and Cypriot investors are also present.On the Black Sea coast and in the most renowned ski resorts, we traditionally meet many Russian buyers.
Foreign buyers are divided into three groups, says Georgij Jankov, regional director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
People who want to move in buy renovated buildings, at a price of between 50 and 100 thousand euros, or old dilapidated houses, at a price of between 5 and 15 thousand euros, which are then renovated.
The criteria are easy access and communication possibilities, proximity to a large city, shops and in general to the local doctor.
The second group includes second-home buyers (since last December, Bulgaria has been listed among the top 10 holiday destinations in Germany).
The third group is made up of commercial investors who buy in the hope of gaining value in the medium or long term.
The price of buildings in the capital is rising steadily as a result of the ever-increasing demand.
Bulgaria has the lowest house prices in the European Union, but over the last five years they have increased by 21 per cent each year.
The increase in real estate prices is essentially greater than the increase in wages.
Fodor and the Hungarian Six Percent
According to the communication of Gábor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Water, the meetings of the professionals will end on Tuesday, however, on Wednesday, after the official opening, the negotiations of the ministers on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries will discuss the Bali Roadmap, which is supposed to define efforts to be made after the Kyoto Protocol emissions reduction period until 2012.
At the moment, there are lively discussions on this subject between developing and developed countries.
The United States also indicated that it was not willing to discuss exact figures at the moment, but was willing to sign an agreement to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25 to 40 percent by 2020 compared with 1990 levels.
Another important topic of the conference is whether developed countries will commit themselves, in addition to reducing emissions, to providing financial and technological assistance to countries in need.
An agreement was also signed on aid to developing countries.
The aid fund defined by the Kyoto Protocol will be managed by a 16-member board of directors, likely under the UN Global Environment Fund (GEF), Piac és Profit (Market and Profit) said.
The six per cent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Gábor Fodor, Minister for the Environment and Water, confirms the EU's ambition to remain the flagship of the global effort to protect the climate and to encourage the signing of the new international agreement before 2009.
The Minister explained that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 2020 compared to 1990 levels, irrespective of the successful signing of the "Agreement after 2012", and is ready to reduce them by up to 30% if other major regions of the world and/or developing countries are also willing to make commitments commensurate with their responsibilities and capacities.
Gábor Fodor recalled that in 1997 the Kyoto Protocol signatory countries had set a total reduction target of 5.2 per cent and all 15 EU members at that time committed 8 per cent less.
Hungary has committed to reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 6 per cent compared with the 1985-87 level, the Ministry of Environment said in a press release.
The stakes are high in Bali because the long-term international agreement on climate policy must be implemented within two years, otherwise the entry into force of the agreement would certainly be delayed beyond 2012. In this case, reduction commitments below the values provided for in the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new international system for reducing emissions, the need for which was highlighted in the new report of the IPCC, the international scientific body that has won the Nobel Peace Prize for dealing with climate change.
The reduction of emissions would be delayed and the increase in the average temperature of the earth by more than 2 degrees Celsius could no longer be avoided, which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irreversible consequences.
The British Army is recruiting on YouTube
British Army units are sharing video recordings from their operations in Iraq and Afghanistan on the video-sharing site in an effort to make themselves popular.
First, the British Air Force (RAF) has become a fan of YouTube, with special forces in Afghanistan uploading videos of their operations against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC reported.
These recordings, taken with miniature cameras mounted on the helmet, are monitored at the Air Force Headquarters in Kandahar and then transferred to London where compatriots upload them to the Internet.
Political message is unavoidable
The Air Force soldiers have already uploaded 139 videos via this channel and their "channel" has been watched by over 75,000 people.
The UK Ministry of Defence signed up as Defence Headquarters in spring 2007 and it releases videos on operations in Iraq and Afghanistan while the Commonwealth Office and the International Peace Keeping Force in Iraq (IPF) also have their own YouTube channels.
Mission to Afghanistan
According to the original purpose of the Air Force, the videos were posted on the net for recruitment purposes. According to the Ministry of Defence, they were also used to make the general public aware of the real purposes of the military presence abroad.
The propaganda that is spread through this channel costs practically nothing compared to the usual television recruitment ads, said Gordon Mackenzie, a defence consultant, but it also inevitably carries a political message, since it justifies in a special way the legitimacy of military operations decided by the government.
The Americans have a game.
The army is annoyed because, apart from the carefully composed and censored videos, amateur videos have been passed on the sharing site that also show, for example, the death of soldiers: in the official propaganda films, a bit hypocritical, the officers do not avoid talking about the losses but they never show the bloody side of the battle.
In fact, many videos had already been posted online showing the real-life operations areas in Iraq and Afghanistan, but the British Army only recently got busy uploading these videos.
The Americans do the recruitment a little differently using the free downloadable shoot 'em up game America's Army, in which the player can directly take the place of the soldiers in a more or less real simulation.
Christmas raffle and donuts in the ministry
Mónika Lamperth, Minister of Labour, does not seem to be sentimental: instead of celebrating Christmas, she will hold a year-end meeting with her employees who will be able to say goodbye to 2007 with donuts and coffee.
Another ministry will host a party with live music, yet another will charm officials with a raffle and offer a drink to create a Christmas atmosphere.
Party, Christmas atmosphere, concerts and buffets, that's how the power is entertained.
The public authorities are also preparing for Christmas.
This year, the largest Christmas party will be hosted by the Ministry of Defence but Ministry employees will not be invited.
At Christmas, Orphans, the children of fallen soldiers will receive gifts, for Missionary Christmas, family members of soldiers currently serving in foreign missions are invited and a press reception will also be held.
The Ministry is planning a budget of 25 million forints to create the atmosphere for the end of the year.
Compared with other ministries, the National Development Agency (NFÜ) and the Ministry of Economy and Transport (GKM) will celebrate.
The GKM party will be held in the House of the Future with a total budget of 4 320 000 forints and, of the 600 employees wholesale, 350 are expected there.
At this party, the Christmas atmosphere will be strict, there will be actors and also a raffle.
The NFÜ Christmas cost 4,700,000 forints and was held on Wednesday in the National Council of Justice (ILO) building with concerts and a dinner.
The rent of the hall cost one million forints, the rest was spent on the more than four hundred guests.
We have information that a department of the NFÜ is invited to another Christmas party organised with European money by the National Centre for Economic Development, the company responsible for the tendering process.
The building of the Théâtre de la Gaîté was rented for this purpose.
This information has not been confirmed by MAG Zrt as we have not been able to reach the person responsible.
The costume is not mandatory
The ILO building was not only the home of the NFÜ but also of the Ministry of Justice and the Police, which instead of a Christmas party organised a St. Luke's Day ball on 7 December.
The ILO did not charge them for the use of its halls.
There were 500 people at that ball.
The party began with the minister's welcoming words and the dinner was followed by a dance night with live music.
Answer to [origo's] question: party attire was not mandatory at all at this ball.
The Ministries of Health, Labour and Local Government are planning a sober party.
The Ministry of Health will organize a show and a party for its employees, inside its walls, for 400,000 forints.
However, Mónika Lamperth, Minister for Labour, does not officially invite her employees to a Christmas party but to a year-end work meeting.
One hundred and eighty people are expected to be invited to a coffee and donuts, the press service reported, and the party will cost only 350,000 forints.
Gordon Bajnai, Minister for Local Government, will simply invite his staff to a drink in the auditorium of the Ministry of Local Government and Land Planning.
The Ministry of Finance (MOF) will hold a Christmas party in its large hall where 436 employees are expected.
He plans to spend 2,500 forints per guest including a buffet and a drink.
Since János Veres' arrival, the employees of the PM have been celebrating Christmas in the same way every year.
There is no festive atmosphere, the official character is reinforced not only by the Minister's presentation but also by the time of the party taking place in the afternoon.
The Ministry of Agriculture will hold a reception on January 20th to celebrate the new year, the Christmas party will not take place.
The reception will be held at Vajdahunyad Castle, located in the City Wood, and according to the Ministry's communication, 1,000 forints per person are calculated for the 100 guests.
According to the press service, it will be a very simple cocktail party to which only foreign diplomats accredited in Hungary will be invited.
The annual cocktail party begins with a few words of welcome from the minister followed by a simple meal.
The Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Ministry of Education and Culture do not celebrate Christmas at all, their respective press services told [origo].
The press service of the Ministry of Environment did not know the price of the official Christmas party.
However, over four hundred people were invited to the party at the Museum of Decorative Art.
The forces of the mega strike are gathering
The unions of the League and the National Association of Workers' Councils will form their strike committee on Friday, which will be responsible for coordinating the indefinite strike on Monday.
On Saturday, a general protest meeting will be held and on Monday, the day of the final vote on the health insurance law, the strike will begin.
This action will certainly cause significant traffic jams as rail traffic will be almost completely stopped and the employees of BKV (public transport company) will also strike until 1pm.
The trade unions of the league will announce on Friday afternoon the details of their strike on Monday, organized with the National Association of Workers' Councils.
The strike committee of LIGA-MOSZ will also be formed, it will serve as the coordinator of the actions of Monday.
On Saturday, a general protest meeting will be held and, starting on Monday, the organisations joining the strike will stop work indefinitely if they cannot reach an agreement with the government.
This means that the date of the end of the strike, from the day of the parliamentary vote on the law on health insurance, is not defined.
If the National Assembly does not pass the health insurance law, the unions will immediately withdraw the strike call.
If the law is passed, the strike committees will meet and decide what to do next.
According to the Monday agenda of the National Assembly, it is likely that the vote on the health insurance law will not take place until late in the evening, or even at night.
Due to the strike scheduled for Monday, major traffic jams are expected: the railways will stop work for an indefinite period and during the morning part of public transport in Budapest and more than half of the Volán companies are likely to be shut down.
At the same time, in different parts of the country, half the road will also be blocked.
Many unions and civil society organisations have joined the strike call, the list of which is constantly updated on the League's website.
Some organisations are reporting indefinite strikes, others have declared a temporary stoppage of work.
Until Thursday afternoon, the MÁV (Hungarian Railways) and the Free Union of Rail Workers (VDSZSZ) had not been able to reach an agreement on minimum services, and as the Christmas holidays approach, more and more people are taking the train.
According to current reports, Budapest public transport will strike from the start of service until 1 p.m., Budapest Airport between 7 and 9 a.m., the Electricity and Thermal Energy Industrial Unions of the League will strike for four hours, the Teachers' Union and the Democratic Teachers' Union have called for a strike for 2 hours and from 2 to 8 hours respectively.
The National Association of Doctors will strike in the whole country in alternation, the Union of Health and Social Employees (EDDSZ) attached to the SZEF will strike for two hours.
The most important of the four demands, formulated by the League, demands that the government withdraw its proposal for health reform and submit a new concept to social debate.
The second demand is that the new method of calculating pensions, to be introduced from next year, be introduced in several stages.
The third demand is a guarantee, in terms of early retirement, that the jobs that deserve it can be transferred into the system before 2010.
The fourth ground of action is the rejection by the Free Union of Railroad Workers (VDSZSZ), affiliated to the League of Trade Unions, of the proposal of the Ministry of Economy and Transport concerning secondary railway lines and the expectation of another proposal.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard has increased the risk to the country
According to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital, the activity of the Hungarian Guard, which was set up last August with the support of Jobbik Magyarországért Mozgalom (Movement for a Better Hungary), increases, in several respects, the political risk of Hungary and the region.
In its  risk warning , the company points out that, in relation to the Hungarian Guard's activity, the biggest political risk is already that  in the short term aggressive ethnic clashes may occur as a result of the aggravation of the already existing ethnic tension between the Gypsy and non-Gypsy population of Hungary .
The research institute added that the Hungarian Guard's political strategy likely to provoke this situation is the main reason.
As they say, this is explained by one of the main shortcomings of Hungarian political actors:  public actors have passed the public debate on the Roma issue to representatives of radical and extremist political groups who have based a political strategy on the dispute between Gypsies and Hungarians .
The problem is aggravated, normal dialogue becomes impossible, extremists are strengthened and aggressive conflicts are more likely, they say.
However, according to the research institute, the increased attention of the Hungarian and international media has led to a significant deterioration of the image of Hungary abroad, in particular as regards confidence in the country's stability and democratic maturity.
They recall that, following increased publicity given to the reorganisation of Hungarian radical and extreme right groups since autumn 2006, numerous associations have been formed in Hungary since summer 2007 under the name of  National Association for Self-Defense .
 The common feature of these gatherings is that they define themselves as a civilian organization while publicly declaring the preparation of their members for defense missions (catastrophes, national defense, defence of order), armed if necessary, and also evoking the incompetence of the police, the army, or the state, they added.
They pointed out that everything was being done in a way that, based on the public's resentment of politics and parties, seeks to disguise different political ambitions under a civil aspect.
The emphasis on civil status and association status is therefore not only to avoid the legal pitfalls of registering such associations in court but also to constitute a political strategy.
The analysis indicates that the activity of the Hungarian Guard is a factor which also increases the risk in relation to neighbourly relations.
 In recent months, many neighbouring countries have cited the Hungarian Guard as a potential source of risk and ultra-nationalist political actors in some neighbouring countries have sought to justify their anti-Hungarian policies by referring to the constitution of the Hungarian Guard.
This is affecting the political stability of the region, they added.
According to the research institute, the creation of the Hungarian Guard is not a unique phenomenon in Central and Eastern Europe, political risks have increased throughout the region.
As they say, the functioning of the Hungarian Guard is similar, for example, to the activity of the Bulgarian National Guard, whose constitution was declared by the Bulgarian National Union (BNU) in August 2007.
The many Roma riots that broke out in a part of Sofia (Kraszna Poljana) led to the formation of the Bulgarian Guard.
Taking advantage of these events, the UNB decided to form a guard, saying that the organization's goal is  national self-defense .
