The party isn't marked in red everywhere
In Hungary, the law defines exactly which holidays are to be observed, and around the holidays it has become common to reorganize the working days, the number of which will be reduced next year.
The holidays are not uniform in the EU and the US either.
Hungarian legislation distinguishes between national and state holidays and public holidays.
Holidays are often associated with religious holidays or important historical events.
In Hungary we celebrate the New Year, the last day of the year ending and the first day of the new year are also days of rest, especially the last day so that the wake-up callers can rest peacefully.
In addition, in a year we have a total of eleven festivals marked in red.
March 15 is a national holiday commemorating the 1848 revolution, as is October 23 which is also the day of commemoration of the 1956 revolution.
On August 20th, we celebrate our state's constitution, May 1st is Labor Day, and on November 1st and 2nd, we remember our family members and friends who have passed away.
In addition, we have two days on Easter, Pentecost and Christmas.
Since the days of our state, national or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, according to the calendar, it has become common to reorganize the working days in cases where there is only one working day left before or after the holiday marked in red.
It is true that we pay the price for extended weekends by working or going to school on the Saturday before the extended weekend.
For many years the Minister for Labour has been making a special regulation on the replacement of days before and after the holidays.
The law applies to all employers and their employees, to civil servants and to persons working in the public service.
However, it does not apply to service companies, which are non-stop and in service by virtue of their vocation, and also to holidays.
This year, working days will be changed only around the end of the year: from 24 December, life is almost stopped in the whole country because according to experience most people are working overtime or taking holidays they have saved for these purposes so that they can spend the days between Christmas and New Year's Day at home.
Next year many holidays will fall in the middle or at the end of the week, so there will be fewer changes in working days compared to this year.
The calendar will be reorganised for the first time around Labour Day to allow employees to stay home for four days in a row.
Saturday 25 April will be a working day, with a rest day on Friday 2 May.
Another change is planned for 23 October: Saturday 18 October will be a working day replacing Friday 24.
But next year, the end of the year is marked by holidays, because from 24 December everyone will have a non-stop break, even if New Year's Day falls on a Wednesday.
Six trivial things that can terribly annoy coworkers
E-mails we forget to send, voice messages we never receive, innocent lies that almost annoy us more: these are things that  embellish  the daily life of a workplace.
The question is whether you get used to the trouble or you take the challenge and consciously avoid ambiguous situations, causing trouble to others.
Examples.
Sorry, I forgot to tell you, you got a call from the marketing department, says a colleague.
That you missed an appointment?
At best, he's sorry and tries to fix things by calling the marketing department and telling them he forgot to pass the message (the least common solution).
In most cases, the matter is settled with an apology.
Before you give a hard explanation, it is good to think about how you might cause discomfort to your coworkers and to make an effort to avoid it.
You borrowing something that doesn't belong to you?
There's nothing more annoying than trying to get a file or a desk tool or a phone and you can't find them anywhere.
Remember the day before you put the stapler on the desk and it was gone the next morning?
You happen to find your pen that you thought you lost on your colleague's desk?
Do not take anything from your fellow workers without asking, or they will be right to be angry with you for taking their property.
Don't bring envelopes or post-it notes in your pocket, because it can be annoying if there aren't any left and you need them right away.
You're talking about the privacy of your coworkers?
There are no good ways to stop gossip from spreading.
Who did what, with whom?
Or why?
Don't tell everyone your information (assumptions) about the private life of your coworkers!
If a fellow confides his secrets to you, do not abuse his confidence.
Bury the information you shared with your colleagues in your heart and do not discuss it with them in their absence even if your colleagues also know about it.
You're calling in sick for no good reason?
When you call the office and you declare yourself ill on the pretext of a headache because you feel bad or you feel you need to rest that day, think about the fact that your work, your urgent business, your final assignments must be done by someone else for you.
Don't bother your coworkers!
If you know in advance that you will not be able to go to work the next day or that something may happen that will require you to stay at home, do not forget to inform your boss and your coworkers so that they will not be surprised that you are absent the next day.
Flirting, teasing, the phone
You're in your work, but the teasing of your coworkers is just a way to get you out of it?
Have you unwittingly witnessed a conversation on the phone that you would have preferred not to hear?
Do not disturb your coworkers with your whining, singing, talking out loud (over their heads), kicking, cursing, or expressing your displeasure aloud.
They can be annoying even if your colleagues are not immersed in a project (writing, design, organization).
You're blaming others for a mistake?
If your work is not done by the deadline, you forget to send an important e-mail or message, do not blame anyone for this forgetfulness!
Don't blame him for the possible chaos in the office or your noisy coworkers!
Confess your mistake and if it has caused others to be hurt, make amends.
Ask how you could fix your mistake, fix your negligence.
You feel too at home at the office?
Wearing jogging shoes is comfortable at home but not in the office!
Don't wear a comfortable jogging suit even if your job allows it!
Don't be neglected, show respect for your co-workers and yourself by dressing properly, and if your job requires it, wear nice, elegant clothes when you go to work!
If you want to live up to expectations, you're not interesting anymore.
