The treacherous trader risked billions because of his inferiority complex
A fraud who hides his identity.
So calls his former employee the French giant Société Générale, owner of the Czech bank Komerční banka.
The bank lost almost five billion euros because of him.
It seems rather that Kerviel is merely a great player who wanted to match his colleagues, and who, moreover, cannot be regarded as incompetent.
Unlike all the big banks, he recognized the crisis in the U.S. mortgage market in time.
"He's fragile", his superiors suggested, who reported him to the police.
However, according to Kerviel's testimony reported by French media, including Le Monde, his transactions produced a profit of 1.6 billion euros at the end of last year.
The crisis extends beyond the United States
"All I wanted was to make money for my bank", he said in the deposition.
Last summer, he managed to profit from the American crisis to make half a billion euros.
In fact, he sensed the opportunity at the beginning of the year.
Reports began to emerge in February that so-called sub-prime mortgages, which are given to low-income customers or to those who have had problems in repayment in the past, would have problems.
But this crisis should not affect the economy as a whole.
Kerviel didn't believe in it and he bet it.
At the end of the year, the company's profits amounted to 1.6 billion euros.
"As soon as I earned my first half a billion dollars, I didn't know how to announce it", Kerviel confides, adding that he, of course, kept nothing for himself".
During the interrogation, he admitted to falsifying the reports to avoid detection.
He managed to fool his superiors, although the Eurex stock exchange began to take an interest in his transactions.
Whoever doesn 't risk anything has nothing .
Was he afraid of being discovered?
I'm not sure.
"I thought that just getting 1.6 billion for the bank would satisfy them".
Why is he willing to risk so much?
He only got to his post gradually.
He started working at Société Générale in 2000 right after finishing his studies at the University of Lyon.
His annual salary was about $51,000.
Two years later, he was already an assistant trader, and in 2005, he became a freelance trader with an annual salary of $90,000.
But he knew he would never make as much as the others.
"From the first interview in 2005, I knew I was far less valued than others.
In view of my university education and my professional and personal background", Kerviel told investigators.
But soon after he took office, he won his first major victory.
Thanks to Allianz shares, he made half a billion euros betting on the fall of that stock in the London bombings.
And the mechanism was triggered -- he wanted more.
As long as you win, we'll leave you alone.
"It was like a snowball effect", he told the police.
But the superiors knew everything, or rather, they suspected it.
"While I was winning, they pretended to close their eyes".
Then came the first of the year.
He loses a billion euros in one day.
In mid-January, after the weekend, he decides to hide the money.
When he gets to work on Monday, he's not a bank employee anymore.
A few days later, the bank announced that it had lost $5 billion because of him.
And how did we find out?
He's become suspicious because of his vacation.
"Last year I only took 4 days off.
A trader who does not take a holiday is a trader who does not want to leave his book to another", Kerviel concludes.
