Banks want to solve the crisis
The Federal Reserve Bank of the United States, the European Central Bank and the central banks of England, Switzerland and Canada have decided to fight the financial market crisis together.
More than $100 billion will be put into the money markets through auctions.
It will be for banks to sell, by auction, the interest rates at which they are willing to borrow money.
For example, the US Federal Reserve will send $40 billion to the auction and will provide $24 billion to the European and Swiss central banks.
This is the first time since the September 11 attacks that the central banks of individual countries have decided to take such concerted action to prevent or even mitigate the effects of the financial crisis.
"This approach tends to address the major problems of the economy, namely the growing lack of free capital that banks could lend", writes Bernard Baumohl of the consultancy Economic Outlook Group in his client report.
"Consistent action by central banks has reduced the probability of a recession in the United States from 65 percent to about 50 percent", Baumohl adds in his report.
Banks have already lost $60 billion in unpaid loans, mostly in the United States.
Analysts expect further losses in the billions.
"The reason central banks have chosen this approach is that they really need to be aware of what is yet to come", says ABN chief economist Amro Kieran Davies.
"I hear the situation is really bad", he adds.
Central banks fear that if banks themselves have difficult access to loans, they will lend more to their customers.
This would reduce consumption and plunge the US economy into a recession that could affect global economic growth.
The central banks made this choice after failing to lower the London interbank rate, called LIBOR, used to borrow on the interbank market.
This meant that banks were still wary of borrowing from each other, even though the US, Canadian and British central banks had cut their interest rates several times during the autumn.
"It will have the same effect as a further reduction in interest rates", Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
Some analysts do not believe that the central banks' approach will help to avert the crisis, since it does not solve the main problem, which is the collapse of the housing market in the USA.
President Klaus: The debates of environmentalists are incredible
Global climate change is expected to affect developing countries most.
President Václav Klaus has once again spoken out on the issue of global warming.
The criticism this time was directed at the UN international conference on climate change ending in Bali.
In Vienna, where he presented his book The Blue Planet, Not Green, he said that the debates of environmentalists were incredible.
Klaus said that it was not only the structure of the conference, which was made up of a curious mix of representatives from governments and non-governmental organizations, that was unacceptable, but also the fundamental difference between the rhetoric and reality.
"The debate is not structured at all, it is just a rocket of words, replacing solutions to current problems", Klaus said.
The Czech President stressed, during the presentation of his book, that his subject matter is of great importance to him and that is why he is so committed to this cause.
He also expressed satisfaction that his book was also published in German translation, since, he said, "I often meet only with caricatures of my opinions".
Now interested persons can read its positions without being distorted.
Klaus said that although he was not a climate scientist, he felt he had enough motivation to write such a book.
He is an academic who can follow and appreciate scientific papers, he has a background in statistics and he is also an economist.
The main conclusions of the book are, in his view, the following: the climate is constantly changing, changes in it are therefore normal, there is no consensus among all researchers on global warming, the effects of current changes are neither too great nor too serious, so they pose no danger, and, finally, efforts to influence climate change are useless, ineffective and unacceptably costly.
Especially since he has had experience of a totalitarian regime, he considers it unacceptable to impose unverified opinions on others, which he feels is a dangerous infringement on freedom.
In answer to questions from those present, he repeatedly explained that he was not against "reasonable protection of the environment, but against a fundamentalist environmentalism which does not take into consideration the relationship between costs and profits".
Klaus had already spoken about this in Vienna two months ago at the Hayek Institute.
600 thousand people failed to renew their driving licence in time
Six hundred thousand drivers have missed the deadline and have failed to renew their old driving licence, which expires at the end of the year.
We are the last day that people can still apply for renewal, so that the authorities will be able to issue them a new permit before the end of the year.
However, the Ministry is not afraid that hundreds of thousands of drivers without valid licenses will be on the road.
According to the authorities, the driving licence has not been renewed, especially for those who no longer wish to drive.
While municipalities report a drop in the number of applications for renewal of permits, the authorities in the capital are overwhelmed with applications and the number of applications for renewal of permits has been increasing this week.
The City Hall caters to about 2,000 customers a day.
There's a line of about half an hour.
In Prague, nearly 140,000 drivers have not yet renewed their driving licences.
It takes 20 days to get a new permit.
However, it is possible to apply for a release within a shorter period of five days.
In this case, the driver pays an additional five hundred crowns.
Drivers who fail to renew their driving licence by the end of the year and drive without a valid licence will face a fine from January.
The guilty party will be forced to pay a maximum of two thousand crowns.
However, the police officer may also deal with the offence by using a friendly approach.
In the case of an administrative offence, the fine is increased to 2500 crowns.
According to the old reports, even a person who was not going to travel was liable to a fine.
This could have forced her to pay up to 30,000 kroner.
The Ministry had called on the authorities to exercise restraint and to impose fines not exceeding 1000 crowns.
According to Karel Hanzelka, spokesman for the Ministry of Transport, no one is in danger of tens of thousands of fines.
He believed that a driver's license is a document that people can decide whether they want it or not.
It's not like the ID card, which has to be valid without exceptions.
People who no longer wish to drive should return their driving licence.
You can simply bring it or send it to the appropriate municipality.
Driving licences issued between 1964 and 1993 will cease to be valid at the end of the year.
However, drivers are also forced to gradually renew other types of driving licence.
Persons with documents dating from 1994 to 2000 have three years to renew their documents.
The validity of driving licences issued in the years 2001 to 2004 expires in December 2013.
According to Hanzelka, there are about 2.6 million other documents.
