The integration of Slovak pupils into British schools is not going well
The number of children from Eastern European countries in British schools is increasing, which causes the remainder to be concerned about the evolution of local education.
The integration of Eastern Europeans is currently facing a series of obstacles.
British schools are even seeing cases where conflicts between immigrants and descendants of the original inhabitants turn violent.
The case of northern Kent, where the conflict between the Slovak immigrants and the residents is beginning to intensify, illustrates the problem of the integration of children from Eastern Europe.
The quarrels, the bullying and the fighting among the students have translated into the relationships between the parents.
The situation got so bad that the police in Chatham arrested a Slovak woman who was beating a ten-year-old student with a rod.
