In Afghanistan, the Allies are passive, the Americans say
The lack of troops and equipment is affecting the conduct of the mission in Afghanistan, according to the United States.
According to Secretary of Defense Robert Gates, NATO should outline a concrete plan for the years ahead.
The mission in Afghanistan is not going as it should, agreed in Edinburgh, Scotland, by the representatives of the countries that have troops in the southern part of the country.
In addition to the growing opposition from the Taliban, the eight states involved are also discussing future plans and coordination of allies.
While the United States, through Defence Secretary Robert Gates, this week called for NATO troops to be more active, Britain sees strengthening the authority of the Afghan government and stepping up development aid as a priority.
"The developments in Afghanistan are noticeable, but military might can only be part of the solution.
The other is to allow the people to start a new economic and security development themselves", British Defence Minister Des Browne told the BBC.
Ninety percent
The U.S. military has recorded the most intense activity by Afghan insurgents in the past five years.
The number of violent acts has increased by 27 percent compared to last year, to 60 percent in Helmand Province, in the south of the country.
NATO countries have about 40,000 troops in Afghanistan, nearly a quarter of them in the southern part.
The United States, however, maintained that the Allies had reached their absolute limit both in the organization and equipment of their troops.
In particular, they are asking for more helicopters, soldiers and experts to train Afghan troops.
"We will have to think seriously about the concrete goals for the coming period, as well as the ways in which we can achieve them", Gates said.
The Secretary-General of NATO, Jaap de Hoop, made similar remarks today.
"I'm not happy with what we have on the ground and in the air in Afghanistan.
We have about 90 percent of the troops and equipment we would need, and that's not enough", De Hoop told Reuters at the end of three days of talks with the Japanese government in Tokyo.
Who is passive
In recent months there has also been conflict between the countries involved over whether all the allies are doing their best in Afghanistan.
For example, Germany has been criticized for its passivity.
"The Germans have a relatively large presence in Afghanistan.
But they are engaged in areas where violence is minimal, so the combat requirements they are subject to are not as stringent as those in the southern and eastern parts of the country where we operate", Gates said.
The British tabloid Sun this week called German soldiers lazy.
"The Afghan slackers discovered: the Germans play, while ours fight", Sun wrote in a document supplemented by photos of German soldiers playing table tennis.
The German newspaper Bild counterattacked by publishing a photo of a British troop at a rugby match in the southern part of Afghanistan.
Government debt to reach one trillion in 2009
Each Czech is burdened with a government debt of more than 84,000 crowns.
The total debt stood at 842.7 billion crowns at the end of September.
The government had planned to borrow 159.2 billion crowns this year.
As a result of a better than expected development of the state budget savings, the Ministry reduced the planned amount to 152.8 billion crowns.
The Czech Republic's public debt rose to DKK 842.7 billion at the end of September.
In the first nine months of this year, it increased by 40.2 billion crowns.
However, as of June, it had fallen by 13.4 billion kroner.
Today, the Ministry of Finance has confirmed its data on the government debt from the beginning of October.
The burden of a debt of more than 84,000 crowns is on each Czech.
During the whole of last year, the State borrowed more than 111 billion kroner.
"At the moment, it seems that, thanks to a smaller deficit forecast for next year, the one trillion crown mark could be exceeded in 2009 alone.
Next year, the debt is expected to be between 900 billion and a trillion crowns", said Patria Finance analyst David Marek for the iHNed.cz server.
The forecast of Next Finance analyst Vladimír Pikor is similar: "We could exceed one trillion by the end of 2009.
The exact date will depend on the next budget which we do not know yet.
If it appears that the political situation is changing, that politicians are ready to save more, the date could be pushed back to 2010.
But I don't expect that change", he said.
Debts are increasing
The state debt is made up of the central government's debts and is mainly caused by the accumulation of state budget deficits.
The government debt is financed by treasury bills, annuities, direct loans or, for example, by loans from the European Investment Bank.
The internal debt of the State has increased this year from 38.5 billion to 719.4 billion crowns.
The external debt of the State has increased this year from 1,7 billion crowns to 123,3 billion crowns.
The marketable state debt reached 803.3 billion crowns at the end of September and decreased by 13.7 billion crowns from June.
The average maturity of the government debt was 6.5 years.
"Total debt has increased year-on-year from the first to the third half of the year by 13 per cent, which is far too high a figure given the current health of the economy.
Interestingly, the increase is mainly generated by annuity securities where it reaches 20 per cent.
It is bad that the debt is growing, but on the other hand it indicates that there will be negotiating material when the pension reform comes", commented Pikora.
Better than we expected.
It follows from the strategy for financing and managing the state debt for 2007 that the government had planned to borrow 159,2 billion crowns this year.
At the beginning of September, however, the Ministry reduced the planned amount to 152.8 billion kroner, as the state budget was more cost-effective than expected.
The sum is mainly the deficit in the State budget, which will obviously reach 76 billion crowns this year, instead of the 91.3 billion crowns originally planned.
The second is the maximum sources foreseen for the Czech Consolidation Agency, namely DKK 13.3 billion, the DKK 10 billion pension reserve, DKK 43 billion for the financing of state pension securities and DKK 1.8 billion for the repayment of European Investment Bank loans.
