Bush pulls a deal between Israelis and Palestinians
President George Bush announced at the opening of the international peace conference he convened in Annapolis, Maryland, on Tuesday that the Israelis and Palestinians had finally agreed on a joint declaration.
He said that Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Olmert and Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas had agreed to immediately start negotiations with a view to finding a final settlement to the 60-year-old dispute between their two peoples.
In the presence of the two men, Bush promised that he would do everything to help them conclude a "peace treaty" before the end of 2008.
Meanwhile, the Palestinians must dismantle "terrorist infrastructure" and Israel must end its settlement activities, Bush said, reminding both sides of their obligations under the "road map" for peace they agreed to in 2003.
The White House chief stressed that the negotiations between Israel and the Palestinian Authority headed by Abbas would aim "to conclude a peace treaty resolving all outstanding issues, without exception, including the core issues".
This designation covers the three thorny issues at the heart of the Israeli-Palestinian dispute: the future borders of Palestine, the status of Jerusalem, and the fate of Arab refugees driven from their homes in what is now the State of Israel during the 1948 conflict.
Speaking after the US president, Abbas insisted that the upcoming negotiations be "comprehensive and in-depth" and cover all aspects of a settlement, citing "Jerusalem, refugees, borders, settlements, water, security, among others".
Olmert, in turn, pledged that the upcoming talks would be "direct and continuous" and that "an effort would be made to conclude them in the course of 2008".
Bush set the end of 2008 as the deadline for the implementation of his "vision of two states" for Palestinian and Israeli coexistence.
Saudi Arabia has revealed that it had obtained a commitment to this effect from Bush before deciding to attend the conference.
The Arab countries, whose participation in Annapolis was a success for Washington, were behind a plan, endorsed by all the Arab countries, which offered Israel peace in exchange for its withdrawal from all the Arab territories occupied during the 1967 war, including East Jerusalem.
Annapolis marks "a crossroads in the history of the Middle East, especially because it addresses the roots of the conflict and its central aspects", Prince Saud said in an interview with the Saudi Arabian daily.
