A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of secrecy, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which trace the fate of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are open to the public.
The 47 million archival documents, stored on 27 km of line in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were previously only available for a humanitarian purpose, i.e. individually and nominally, at the request of a former victim or his or her beneficiaries.
The 11 states responsible for managing them - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
The process of ratification of this agreement by all States has been completed and the opening has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
The historians' access to Bad Arolsen will allow them to conduct research  on the movement of prisoners, the population of the camps and the health of forced labourers , explains Reto Meistern, the director of these archives run by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, including Germany, opposed the opening of these nominative documents to the public, because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
Like the alleged homosexuality or the mental disability of some deportation victims.
The Gestapo's concentration camp records or arrest warrants were compiled after the war for a practical purpose: to find civilians deported or forced to work and, if necessary, to provide them with proof of their internment, in order to pave the way for compensation.
Today, more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen are still processing tens of thousands of individual applications.
However, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest to some in the scientific community.
