What insurance do I need?
Car insurance, which covers the driver in the event of a potential accident, involves a considerable expense, which will depend on various factors, such as age, sex, length of driving license, marital status, type of vehicle to insure or use, and so on.
Having a car is the main thing.
The problem is that choosing the right car insurance is even more difficult than choosing the right car model.
And the fact is, choosing the right car insurance is even more difficult than choosing the model of the vehicle.
Car insurance is an agreement between an insurance company and the insurer.
This compromise is embodied in an insurance contract, which establishes that the company receives the value of the premium granted and in return becomes liable for the obligation to pay compensation in the event of a loss.
The premium is the price of the insurance, which is determined by taking into account various factors, such as age, sex, length of driving licence, marital status, type of vehicle to be insured or use, among others.
Insurance companies base their prices on statistics, so that the higher the probability of an accident, the higher the payout.
This is why people over 25 and women have to pay lower premiums, since statistics show that these people have a lower rate of claims due to their prudence.
Similarly, from surveys, companies have concluded that married people tend to have fewer accidents than single drivers.
The use of the vehicle will affect the frequency, and therefore the likelihood, of accidents.
Increasing the frequency increases the probability.
There are many variables which insurers take into account when setting the premium price.
This is why the driver must carefully consider the situation in order to choose the car insurance that best suits his profile.
Here we will consider the most important variables when choosing one or the other type of insurance, so that it not only adapts to the characteristics of the insurer but also offers a reasonable price.
Young people under 25 face various disadvantages when contracting affordable insurance, such as low driving experience and a long driving licence.
Although the ideal way to be well insured is to take out a full-risk insurance policy, there are other, more economical options.
The most prudent drivers can opt for all-risk insurance with a deduction, so that they get all-risk insurance coverage at a more affordable price.
This form of agreement implies that the customer pays a part of the amount of the claim.
"The part of the damage that the customer pays will be determined by the value of the premium, which will be higher the lower the amount", says Luis Noguera, the Spanish manager of First Europa, an online insurance broker.
Another option is extended third party insurance, so that the customer provides protection for damage caused to third parties, but for damage to his own car.
In addition, it would be covered against theft, fire and loss of the vehicle.
I'll give you a tip.
If you are under 25 try to be careful and avoid accidents as much as possible, as this will affect the bonus, which may reduce the price of the insurance in the future.
A rebate is a reduction in the basic fare that the company has.
On the contrary, a penalty is an increase in the basic tariff.
'The bonuses and penalties will depend on the company and its profit.
If the company has had a good year, it can afford to increase the bonuses", explains Noguera.
After the age of 25, it becomes easier for drivers to sign an insurance contract, since the rate of accidents is reduced by the experience gained.
For this reason it is best to choose a full-risk insurance policy with honesty.
"Young people usually do not get the benefit of the experience they have after an accident", says the European company's director in Spain, adding that most accidents occur during the second year of driving, after the 'first-time driver's fear' has passed.
However, if the customer is married but has no children, it is preferable that he negotiate a full-risk insurance policy, as long as his financial situation allows it.
Marriages with children are considered by insurers to be the ones with the lowest claims rate, because the premiums will be lower.
In this case the best insurance would be an all-risk insurance with deduction (which can be 300 euros), or an extended third party insurance from the third year of the vehicle's life when the insured has a high level of bonus.
"They have a more relaxed lifestyle and a greater purchasing power to afford the luxury of taking on a larger amount of franchisees", says Luis Noguera.
For pensioners, all-risk insurance with deduction is preferable (this being EUR 150), or extended third party insurance where the insurer has a high level of bonus.
It must be said that car insurance is important, not only because it covers the driver in the event of a potential accident, but also because it represents a significant expense, so it is essential to study properly which insurance is most suitable for us according to our personal situation.
