The new gas deal between Russia and Ukraine is setting the alarm.
A dispute over gas prices is heating up between Ukraine and Russia, increasing the risk of repercussions on fuel exports to Europe.
Most Russian gas exports to the European Union (EU) are transported through pipelines, and each pipeline is scrupulously monitored.
Kiev has announced that if Russia increases the cost of fuel, it will increase transit taxes to Russia.
Last year, a dispute between the two caused a reduction in supplies to the EU countries.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow comes after the Ukrainian government and Russia's gas-supplier Gazprom tried, unsuccessfully, to reach an agreement on the cost of Russian gas supplied to Ukraine for 2008.
Gazprom has stated that it will increase its prices to Ukraine as planned, as it has agreed to pay for 2008 up to 50% more for gas supplies from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts said that this would mean a 40% increase in the costs of imports from Gazprom for Ukraine.
 It is essential for us to use all our arguments during the talks, remembering that we are a country through which most of the gas is transit, said Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoly Kinkh to Reuters news agency.
 The fluctuations in gas costs are probably related to our discussions on transit charges (to Western Europe) via Ukraine 
The last major dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006 caused Gazprom to cut off supplies to Ukraine.
This led to a drop in exports to Western Europe, which led to higher prices.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the European Union's supply.
Russia has the largest gas reserves, although most of them are still underdeveloped.
As a result, Gazprom supplies its own gas from Turkmenistan and other former Soviet states in Central Asia.
The Ministry of Health 'must control its foreign employees.'
The Scottish Health Service needs to improve checks on its non-EU employees to check for criminal records, the audit committee said.
The warning from the Auditor General, Robert Black, came after a foreign doctor working in Scotland was implicated in the Glasgow airport attack in June.
Mr Black further expressed concern that the Scottish Ministry of Health had no precise data on the number of overseas staff it employed.
However, his report highlighted other decisive checks, which were carried out correctly on a sample of employees of five health authorities.
The Auditor General has been conducting checks on extra-Community staff following the Glasgow airport attack.
Bilal Addullah, 28, an Iraqi-born doctor working at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after he drove his jeep into the main terminal gates.
He was one of three doctors who were filmed at the Old Bailey in October, suspected of involvement in various car bombing attempts in the UK.
The Ministry of Health will have to carry out pre-employment checks on overseas staff, to be sure of the validity of their qualifications, experience, and work permits for the UK.
Although the Scottish Ministry of Health uses Scottish Disclosure to carry out checks of criminal records, the agency has no right to obtain such information outside Great Britain.
Among the many warnings, the Auditor General's report now states that committees are required to confront the Office of Past Criminal Procedure, thus allowing employers to undertake checks on various countries.
 Although we have found that some information about staff has been checked, this is not always the case.  announces the report.
Mr Black said that the Scottish Ministry of Health does most of the pre-employment checks it would do itself, but he also added:  our report highlights areas where the system can be improved to ensure that adequate information on certain overseas staff is available to health services.
Mr Peter Terry, President of BMA Scotland, said it was "extremely unlikely" that pre-employment checks could identify employees who might commit future acts of terrorism.
He said 'the report suggests that the pre-employment checks currently being carried out are working well in the Scottish health system and that it is not certain that these warnings can provide any added value.'
The Scottish Health Authority reported employing 1,161 overseas staff, mostly doctors and nurses.
But the Auditor General stressed that these figures certainly need to be revised upwards, partly because of the problems of identifying permanent staff who may or may not choose to stay in our country.
The investigation has shown that the current procedures for controls by the health authorities in Ayrshire and Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire, and Lothian are quite adequate.
These checks are carried out on passports, work permits and qualifications.
The Scottish Government is currently reviewing its policy and system of pre-employment checks for overseas health service personnel.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: "I was excited to do this work following the terrorist attack at Glasgow Airport. 
She added that the Scottish Government, in alliance with the Health Committees, would carefully consider the warnings set out in the report which is due to be published next month, and would commit to ensuring better implementation of the recently updated pre-employment checks, which apply to all employees, including overseas.
