Saudi Arabia blocks 208 terror plots and is trying to stop them
Saudi Arabia yesterday revealed that it had arrested 208 militants involved in organizing cells planning an imminent attack on an oil field, as well as attacks on clerics and the armed forces.
State television from the world's largest oil exporter, said one of the cells smuggled missiles.
Al Qaeda sympathizers have been waging a campaign against the US-allied monarchy since 2003, following the invasion of Iraq.
A cell of eight militants, led by a foreign resident, was planning an attack on an oil site in the Eastern Province, the TV newspaper said.
Saudi Arabia quickly assembled a 35,000-strong force to protect the sites, following a failed Al Qaeda attack in 2006 on the largest oil site in Abqaiq.
The newspaper, citing a statement by the interior minister, said 18 of those arrested belonged to a cell led by a  missile launching expert  who had infiltrated the country.
It's said that the militants were planning to counterattack with eight missiles in the kingdom.
22 of the detainees were allegedly involved in the assassination of clergy and military personnel.
The government has urged clerics to do more against the Saudi-led forces in Iraq, to join Al Qaeda militants fighting against the Allied Forces and the US-allied Shiite Muslim government, which is considered heretical by the hardline Sunni Saudi.
Al Qaeda militants believe that in Saudi Arabia, many clerics have collaborated with the authorities to support the policies of the royal family that dominates the government.
The militants, encouraged by calls against the pro-Western Saudi government by Osama Bin Laden, the Saudi-born leader of Al Qaeda, targeted foreign residential areas, government buildings and energy supply sites.
The armed forces have made significant efforts in the last five months, the spokesman for the interior minister told state television.
Among the detainees are 16 members of the Medina who are organized into a  media cell  aimed at promoting  takfiri thought , the ideology of Sunni Muslim radicals who support the use of violence against infidel and apostate Muslims.
Among the detainees, 32 are accused of subsidizing the militants.
The climate of Venus could reveal the future of the Earth.
Scientists yesterday declared that Venus was certainly a pleasant planet to live on.
Data from the European spacecraft in orbit have shown that the planet is certainly twice as small as the Earth, contrary to previously thought.
Venus is the closest planet to Earth.
These two worlds are practically the same size, with similar orbits, although Venus is closer to the Sun.
Scientists now believe that billions of years ago, Venus might have had conditions similar to Earth's, and might even have been habitable.
But the greenhouse effect from carbon dioxide, atmospheric erosion from solar radiation combined with a slower rotation has led Venus into a whole different kind of evolution.
Today the planet is without water, ravaged by hurricanes and lightning storms, and has a surface temperature hot enough to melt lead.
The discoveries of the European Space Agency's Venus Express probe, which has been studying the planet for a year, offer a grim glimpse of the potential future of the Earth due to catastrophic climate changes.
Professor Fred Taylor of the Department of Physics at Oxford University, one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission, said: "We are beginning to understand why the climate of Venus is so different from that of Earth, although the planets themselves are practically similar.
 Our new data allows us to establish a scenario that billions of years ago, Venus would have been originally identical to Earth, perhaps even with a habitable surface. 
