In the United States, their case remains an open question for the investigation that was launched following the collapse of Enron in 2001.
The charges brought against them in 2002 made it clear to Fastow that he was the subject of a government investigation into the Enron debacle.
The charges against the bankers, nicknamed the "natwest three", state that they came to Houston in 2000 to set up a fraudulent scenario with Fastow and his former right-hand man, Michael Kopper.
NatWest Greenwich invested in a subsidiary of an Enron partner controlled by Fastow, who was the mastermind behind many fraudulent scenarios, which helped him rig the bankruptcy proceedings.
In early 2002, the bank had estimated its interest in the branch as zero, but in fact the three British banks already know its value.
