Venus is the infernal twin of Earth.
Despite its hostile atmosphere, Venus is more like Earth than previously thought. The European spacecraft Venus Express has detected lightning flashes in the atmosphere and wind vortices at the poles, similar to those seen on Earth in winter.
For nearly three decades, scientists have speculated that there are lightning bolts on Venus.
The European spacecraft Venus Express has proved this today - it detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: lightning on Venus bursts at a height of about 35 miles [56 km] from cloud to cloud, reports Christopher Russell of the University of California, Los Angeles, in the science magazine Nature.
The famous cyprine theory suggests that lightning would have brought life to the Earth. The storm would have stimulated reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, the cornerstone of life.
Not so on Venus. "If life existed, it must have been at a very early date in history", explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
The atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than that of Earth, and temperatures can reach 500 degrees Fahrenheit [500°C].
"Venus may be the infernal twin of Earth, but it's still a twin", Russell said.
Why Venus, which is so similar to Earth in mass and size, was struck by such a different evolution, is the fundamental question of the ASE mission.
The November 2005 launch of the Venus Express was a milestone in the search for Venus, as no other spacecraft had been on the way to explore the planet since the 1990s.
In the opinion of the researchers, the latest research results, which have now been presented in several articles in "Nature", do more than emphasize the uniqueness of Venus in the solar system.
They also show that the Earth has more in common with our neighboring planet than was initially thought.
So, in addition to the windstorm already known at the North Pole, researchers have found a cloudstorm at the South Pole, which is spinning even faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of the air currents in the Earth's hemispheres in winter, writes a team of researchers around Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second planet in our solar system is almost as massive as Earth and, with a diameter of some 12,000 miles [12,100 km], almost as big.
The planet called the evening star or morning star orbits the sun in just 225 days.
However, it rotates much more slowly on its own - a day on Venus lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus, with a surface temperature of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, is hardly like Earth, scientists speculate that the two planets formed under similar conditions.
On both, water accumulated and remained on Earth as oceans, but was lost in space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide has been attached to the Earth as carbonate, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
