Richard Gere is just not cynical enough.
With "The Hunting Party" and "Killing Peace", two films again address the war in the Balkans.
But neither is convincing.
Either the projects are too much based on action and senseless gunfire or they are too tearful.
Here, even Richard Gere in The Hunting Party can't help it.
The good news is that although the war criminals Karadzic and Mladic are still hiding in the mountains of the Balkans, it is precisely here, in the most bleak backdrop of the Bosnian war, that the actor Richard Gere is found.
We had finally lost sight of the most handsome man of the 1980s, because far too many gentle, futile roles in films with female sentiment and far too many press conferences on the theme of Buddhism robbed him of the urge to show himself.
Today Richard Gere is suddenly the most important argument for watching "The Hunting Party" anyway - when the hunter becomes the hunted (why do today's movies have to be as long and confusing as locomotive drivers' collective agreements?)
He delivers a beautiful, wink-filled portrayal: at bottom, his war reporter character Simon Hunt is what Gere might have become, had not fate and the film industry been so kind: a man whose best days have long been behind him, but who, even as a ruined monument to his decline, has nevertheless kept visible remnants of his former charm.
But despite this, "The Hunting Party" continues alongside the German production "Killer Peace", which also releases this week, the endless sequence of failed films about the Balkan war.
"Killer Peace" can be quickly made into a trial: the film tells the story of two German soldiers in Kosovo (Adrian Topol, Max Riemelt), who save a Serb woman from Kosovar snipers, with whom one of them soon falls in love again.
Although it is welcome that the Serbs are not here for once presented as the sole cause of all evil, this film as flat as a television film is lost far too quickly in the action and the senseless exchange of fire.
It's still a kind of Cobra 11 Alarm without a highway but with a war instead.
On the contrary, we can look at the perfect example of "The Hunting Party", why there was never a really good movie about the Balkan war.
The story of the three American war reporters, who condition themselves to track down the top war criminal "the fox", might have become, with another director and another writer (both Richard Shepard), at another time a new "Apocalypse Now".
Because the stories are strikingly similar: two males go into the forest in small teams, to accomplish something that the military can't do, and for both males, it becomes a journey into madness.
One of the reasons "The Hunting Party" failed is that we simply don't let Simon Hunt be the heart-shaped, cynical outcast we're introduced to at the beginning.
No, the script must also give him a romantic affair with a Bosnian woman who was later murdered.
Then "The Hunting Party" becomes definitely bad, when the reporter, in the space of the last five minutes, by an accelerated process, achieves what NATO, the CIA and all the bounty hunters in the world have failed to do in five years: catch the war criminal and leave him for just revenge to the Bosnian Muslims.
It is so bad that we should go to the International Criminal Court in The Hague for crimes against film logic.
In that case, the film has too deep a human concern.
He wants to denounce that Karadzic and Mladic are still at large, and he suspects the Americans and the French (here they must be exceptionally in agreement) are not conducting the hunt intensively enough because of secret political agreements.
But the well-intentioned and the bad this time are so similar that we are reminded of a famous poem by Brecht.
It tells of a wooden mask of an Asian demon on the poet's work table: "Compassionate, I see the veins of the forehead swollen, clearly: how tiring it is to be mean".
Movies like "The Hunting Party" have exactly those tummy-headed, but insinuating how tiring it is to be good.
The problem is not limited to the genre of films about the Balkan war.
Recently, it was reported in this paper that all Hollywood movies about Iraq were big flops.
We can add that there have never been any good films about South Africa.
And it's always worth it, because when a star hangs out in a crisis center or a minefield, then something like "Rangoon" with Patricia Arquette, "Jenseits aller Grenzen" with Angelina Jolie or "Blutdiamanten" with Leonardo DiCaprio.
It is possible that all these conflicts are still just too close in time.
Anyway, it was still decades before Hollywood could make a good Holocaust film with "Schindler's List".
Some films are still to mature - those that are now considered classics about Vietnam, such as "The Deer Hunter", "Apocalypse Now", or "Full Metal Jackett", were by no means universally celebrated as masterpieces in their time.
But maybe we know too much today about the conflicts of the world, where every slaughter comes live on two screens at the same time at home,
And it made the writers feel the lack of scruples they need to tell great stories.
"To be or not to be" or "The Dictator" actually became as good as that, too, because Lubtisch and Chaplin still didn't know how dominant the Nazi regime really was.
Maybe you don't have to be good to make good movies.
Perhaps we should have the sarcastic, distant artistic gaze of novelist Lawrence Norfolk.
When asked about the parallel between his historical novel "Dictionnaire de Lemprière" and the Balkan War, he replied: "It's just that some things never change".
"The big cities will always be horribly dangerous, men will always be murdered in a horrific way and war will always reign in Yugoslavia".
