These aren't Warhols boxes.
The guy who connects the concepts of Sweden and wooden box, he thinks of IKEA, but not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
Right now, wooden boxes made in Sweden are casting a shadow over Warhol's catalogue.
A large part of the ninety Brillo-Boxes of "Type Stockholm" listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper Expressen questioned the authenticity of Andy Warhol's 1968 Brillo-Boxes a few months ago, internal research at the Moderna Museet in Stockholm has now led to a disappointing result: the six Brillo-Boxes, which former museum director Pontus Hulten gave to Moderna Museet in 1995, are copies - as well as a large part of the hundreds of other Brillo-Boxes of the "Stockholm Type" that circulate on the international art market.
Ancient history is entangled, a bewildering chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo-Boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes, which are based on the red-blue-white design of the "Brillo" powder soap boxes.
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet in 1968 showed - with Warhol's agreement - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: These did not come from Warhol (for financial reasons), but had been delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
It was not artwork, but rather models, exhibition samples.
At the same time, Warhol had given permission in 1968 to produce some Brillo wooden boxes in Sweden, which were not exhibited at Moderna Museet.
Witnesses from the time speak today of about fifteen wooden boxes which at the time would have rightfully entered the history of art and auctions, as authorized original Andy Warhol Brillo-Boxes, with the designation "Type Stockholm".
Some of these have sold at auction for over $100,000.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the Pontus Hultén Museum later claimed, wrongly, that about a hundred wooden boxes had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol would later give to him.
In fact, the 105 Hultén boxes were produced in Malmö in 1990 for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By this time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Besides the six Brillo-Boxes in the museum, Lars Byström, chief curator of the Moderna Museet, examined three other pieces from Swedish private collections, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their laminated panels were first printed and polished, then applied with a brush of white oil paint.
The texture of the 1990 copies reveals that the paint was applied directly to the laminated panels without a backing, using a paint roll - and it is not oil paint, but acrylic.
"These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol Brillo-Boxes", suggests Moderna Museet director Lars Nittve. "Unless the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York decides otherwise, Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibition materials".
Already in July the Authentication Board announced that it would investigate the "heavy charges" that would be raised in the case of the powder soap boxes.
But since then, there's been an inexorable silence.
